each disbursement from such funds. The record must be kept for the period of time as
required and determined by the comptroller of the treasury.
SECTION 2. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 58, Chapter 2, is amended by adding
the following new part:
58-2-1001. Findings and purpose.
(a) The general assembly declares that disaster mitigation and resiliency from
the devastation caused by Hurricane Helene are of the highest priority to this state and
the people of Tennessee.
- 2 - 005314

(b) The general assembly finds that rapidly deploying grant funding to eligible
residents in counties most affected by Hurricane Helene is a meaningful step toward
mitigating the loss and devastation experienced by residents of such counties.
58-2-1002. Definitions.
As used in this part:
(1) "Director" means the director of the agency;
(2) "Eligible individual" means a natural person who is:
(A) A resident of a county for which the federal or state
government issued a declaration of emergency as the result of the
impacts of Hurricane Helene; and
(B) Eligible for assistance in accordance with rules promulgated
by the agency under this part; and
(3) "Fund" means the Hurricane Helene Rapid Response Fund, created
pursuant to ยง 58-2-1003.
58-2-1003. Hurricane Helene rapid response grant fund.
(a) There is created in the state treasury the Hurricane Helene Rapid Response
Fund, to be administered by the agency for the benefit of eligible individuals recovering
from the devastation caused by Hurricane Helene. The agency shall award grants from
the fund to eligible individuals in accordance with this part.
(b) It is the intent of the general assembly that the fund is funded by an
appropriation of fifty million dollars ($50,000,000) for fiscal year 2025-2026, and may be
funded by additional appropriations in subsequent fiscal years.
(c) Money remaining in the fund at the end of the fiscal year must not revert to
the general fund, but must remain in the fund for the issuance of grants in accordance
with this part. Money in the fund must be invested by the state treasurer pursuant to title
9, chapter 4, part 6, for the sole benefit of the fund.
58-2-1004. Administration and rulemaking.
- 3 - 005314

(a) The director shall develop an electronic application form for eligible
individuals to apply for a grant from the fund that may be submitted electronically
through an online portal on the agency's website. The application and portal must be
created within the existing resources of the agency.
(b) The agency shall adopt rules for the administration of grants from the fund,
including rules:
(1) Prescribing additional qualifications of an eligible individual;
(2) Prescribing guidelines outlining the qualified uses for such funds,
including reimbursements for bonafide expenditures of eligible individuals;
(3) That facilitate the expedient and rapid disbursement of grants to
eligible individuals, including rules to expedite the review and approval of
applications; and
(4) That ensure that the issuance of grant funds are not a duplication of
benefits under federal law.
(c) Rules adopted by the agency under subsection (b) may be emergency rules,
and must be adopted in accordance with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act,
compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
SECTION 3. This act is not an appropriation of funds, and funds must not be obligated
or expended pursuant to this act unless the funds are specifically appropriated by the general
appropriations act.
SECTION 4. For purposes of promulgating rules and carrying out administrative duties
necessary to effectuate this act, this act takes effect upon becoming a law, the public welfare
requiring it. For all other purposes, this act takes effect July 1, 2025, the public welfare requiring
it.
